    md("## Exercises\n\n1. Create a 5×5 identity matrix using `np.eye`. Then multiply it by 7 and verify the result.\n2. Generate 1 000 samples from a standard normal distribution. Compute the Z-scores: `z = (x - mean) / std`. Confirm the Z-scores have mean ≈ 0 and std ≈ 1.\n3. Without using a loop, compute the Euclidean distance between every pair of rows in a (4, 3) matrix. *Hint*: Broadcasting.\n4. Given a 2D array of exam scores (shape `(30, 5)`), find the student (row) with the highest average score.\n\n## Reflection Questions\n- Why does NumPy store data in a contiguous memory block? What advantage does that give over Python lists?\n- What happens when you slice a NumPy array — do you get a copy or a view? Why does this matter?\n\n---\n**Next →** `03_pandas_essentials.ipynb`"),
